Anthropic's Likely Repository Structure
Almost certainly not a single monorepo — but probably not fully fragmented either. Here's the reasoning:

What's Almost Certainly Separate
The model weights & training infrastructure are virtually guaranteed to be in their own repo(s), isolated for security, access control, and the sheer scale of the tooling involved. Training infrastructure at this level has radically different contribution patterns, review processes, and deployment cadences than product code. Mixing them creates more problems than it solves.

claude.ai (the web product) is likely its own repo or workspace — standard for a consumer product with a dedicated frontend team, independent deployment pipeline, and no need to touch ML infrastructure.

Open-source releases (anthropic-sdk-python, anthropic-sdk-typescript, the MCP spec, etc.) are obviously public standalone repos.

What Might Be Monorepo'd Together
The backend services cluster — API gateway, context assembly, tool orchestration, safety classifiers, memory service — is where a monorepo becomes attractive, for exactly the reasons you know well:

Atomic cross-service changes
Shared internal libraries (auth, logging, config, tracing)
Unified CI/CD and lint/type standards
Consistent dependency management
This cluster probably lives in something like a claude-platform or api-backend monorepo, likely pnpm or Bazel-managed given the polyglot nature (Python + Rust + possibly Go all needing to coexist).

The Likely Actual Structure
anthropic/
├── [private] model-training/          # PyTorch training infra, RLHF, evals
├── [private] inference-engine/        # C++/CUDA kernels, serving runtime
├── [private] claude-platform/         # Monorepo: API gateway, context assembly,
│                                      #   safety, memory, tool orchestration
├── [private] claude-web/              # claude.ai frontend (TypeScript)
├── [private] internal-tooling/        # Dashboards, evals UI, research tooling
├── [public]  anthropic-sdk-python/
├── [public]  anthropic-sdk-typescript/
├── [public]  model-spec/
└── [public]  anthropic-quickstarts/
Why Not One Giant Monorepo
A few forces push hard against it at Anthropic's scale:

Security & access control — the people who should touch model weights are a much smaller, more controlled set than those shipping product features. A monorepo collapses that boundary by default.

Polyglot tooling friction — a Python/CUDA/C++/Rust/TypeScript monorepo is painful. Bazel can handle it but introduces enormous complexity. Most orgs at this size draw a boundary between ML infrastructure (Python-dominant) and product infrastructure (polyglot but lower-stakes) rather than forcing them into one build graph.

Regulatory & compliance pressure — as a frontier AI lab, Anthropic almost certainly has audit requirements around what code touches what. Repo boundaries are a natural enforcement point.

Acquisition/partnership surface — keeping the model training stack isolated makes it cleaner to reason about IP boundaries.

The Honest Uncertainty
The claude-platform backend monorepo is the most speculative part. It's equally plausible that each major service (API gateway, memory, safety, tool orchestration) lives in its own repo with shared libraries published to an internal package registry — the microservices-with-private-registry pattern is common at this scale and avoids monorepo coordination overhead at the cost of cross-service atomic changes.

The truth is probably somewhere in between: a few bounded monorepos organized by team/domain, not one and not fully fragmented.

